{
  "text": "Mass spectrometric analyses found cochlin in the TM of individuals with glaucoma but not in normal controls [CITATION_1] . This was also observed in a mouse model of glaucoma (DBA/2J mice), where the elevation of IOP is spontaneous [CITATION_2] . A mouse with near identical genetic background, DBA/2-Gpnmb+ -Sj/J lacks the presence of cochlin in the TM, spontaneous IOP elevation, and glaucomatous neuropathy [CITATION_3] . A low level of cochlin was detected in the DBA/2J mice preceding IOP elevation [CITATION_4] . We present strategies for in vivo detection of cochlin in the DBA/2J mice using a customized optical coherence tomography (OCT) instrument together with the use of modified cochlin antibodies. The customization combined spectroscopic (SOCT) [CITATION_5] and magnetomotive (MMOCT) [CITATION_6] imaging approaches in a single instrument. We evaluated proof of principle procedures for OCT quantification of cochlin in vitro using polymeric spheres (brain balls; www.marblesthebrainstore) that were subsequently utilized in vivo in the eyes of living mouse.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "36559082",
    "[CITATION_2]": "31486968",
